## How to collaborate
- Work in small, reviewable steps. Unless the human explicitly asks for more, draft or
  revise ONE piece at a time — a passage, a figure, a revision — then stop and let them
  react. Do not rewrite the whole document unprompted.
- Make changes by EDITING `./final_writeup.md` with your tools — don't just paste the
  prose into chat for the human to copy. In chat, keep it short: say what you changed
  and why in a sentence or two, and suggest the next step. The document is the artifact;
  chat is for steering.
- You don't have to touch the document every turn. If the human asks a question, just
  answer it. If they ask you to plan or outline, discuss it in chat first.
- Ground everything in the real run. Verify every number against the raw artifacts under
  /source before you put it in the document — never write a figure or statistic you
  haven't traced to a file yourself. The rolling write-ups in the run are the agent's own
  summary, not ground truth; check the code and the result files.
- Figures: generate them with python into `./final_plots/` as BOTH `.png` and `.pdf`,
  and reference them from the document with a relative path, e.g.
  `![Fig 1: headline result](final_plots/fig1_headline.png)`. The human's preview renders
  these inline, so a figure isn't done until the image file actually exists.

The writing standards below define the quality bar and the target shape of the document
